{"title_page": "Disaster Movie (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2008 American parody film}}\n{{For|the genre|Disaster film}}\n{{pp-pc1}}{{Use American English|date = October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Disaster Movie\n| image = Disaster movie.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer|Jason Friedberg<br />Aaron Seltzer]]\n| producers = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Peter Safran]]\n* Jason Friedberg\n* Aaron Seltzer\n}}\n| writers = {{Plainlist|\n* Jason Friedberg\n* Aaron Seltzer\n}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Matt Lanter]]\n* [[Vanessa Minnillo]]\n* Gary \"G Thang\" Johnson\n* [[Kim Kardashian]]\n* [[Crista Flanagan]]\n* [[Nicole Parker]]\n* [[Ike Barinholtz]]\n* [[Carmen Electra]]\n* [[Tony Cox (actor)|Tony Cox]]\n}}\n| music = [[Christopher Lennertz]]\n| cinematography = Shawn Maurer\n| editing = Peck Prior\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Grosvenor Park Productions|Grosvenor Park]]\n* [[The Safran Company]]\n* 3 in the Box\n}}\n| distributor = [[Lions Gate Entertainment|Lionsgate]]\n| released = {{Film date|2008|08|29}}\n| runtime = 87 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 86:58--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/disaster-movie-2008-0 | title=''Disaster Movie'' (12A) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=August 28, 2008 | accessdate=June 25, 2013}}</ref>\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = $20 million<ref name=\"bom\"/>\n| gross = $34.8 million<ref name=\"bom\"/>\n}}\n'''''Disaster Movie''''' is a 2008 American [[parody film]] written and directed by [[Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer]]. It stars [[Matt Lanter]], [[Vanessa Minnillo]], Gary \"G Thang\" Johnson, [[Crista Flanagan]], [[Nicole Parker]], [[Ike Barinholtz]], [[Carmen Electra]], [[Tony Cox (actor)|Tony Cox]], and [[Kim Kardashian]] in her feature film debut. Released on August 29, 2008 by [[Lionsgate]], the film is a parody of the [[disaster film]] genre and [[pop culture]]. \n\nThe film was panned by critics and audiences for its forced humor, excessive references and poor directing, with many considering it to be worse than the previous movies created by Seltzer and Friedberg,<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/SHOWBIZ/Movies/09/25/decades.worst.movies.tomatoes/ | title=Site picks worst movies of the decade | work=CNN | date=September 25, 2009 | accessdate=September 25, 2016}}</ref> as well as [[List of films considered the worst|one of the worst films of all time]]. The movie received six nominations for the [[29th Golden Raspberry Awards]]. It grossed nearly $35 million against a budget of $20 million.<ref name=\"bom\"/>\n\n==Plot==\nIn the year [[10,000 BC (film)|10,001 B.C.]], a [[caveman]] runs away from a predator through a plain and immediately gets into a fight with [[Michael Van Wijk|Wolf]] ([[Ike Barinholtz]]). After defeating him, the caveman then encounters the predator, a [[Saber-toothed cat|saber-toothed]], [[gasoline]]-drinking [[Amy Winehouse]] ([[Nicole Parker]]), who informs him that the [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|world will end]] on August 29, 2008 and that their fate lies in a [[Indiana Jones and the Kingdom of the Crystal Skull|Crystal Skull]]. The sequence is then revealed to be a dream of [[everyman]] Will ([[Matt Lanter]]) in the present day. He then finds out that his girlfriend Amy ([[Vanessa Minnillo]]) is having an affair with [[Flavor Flav]] (Abe Spigner), and she breaks up with Will because he is not admitting his true feelings for her.\n\nLater that day, Will has a \"[[My Super Sweet 16|Super Duper Sweet Sixteen]]\" party at his house, despite being 25. The guests include [[Juno (film)|Juney]] ([[Crista Flanagan]]), [[Phil McGraw|Dr. Phil]] (John Di Domenico), Will's best friend Calvin (Gary \"G Thang\" Johnson), and [[Anton Chigurh]] (Barinholtz), among others. During the party, Amy arrives with her new boyfriend, a [[Calvin Klein]] underwear model. The party then comes to a halt when the room shakes and the lights go out. A bulletin on the radio claims there is a [[meteor shower]] and it is the end of the world. Soon after, the city starts to [[The Day After Tomorrow|freeze over]], and Will, Juney, Calvin, and Calvin's girlfriend Lisa ([[Kim Kardashian]]) retreat to a garage for shelter. When Juney mentions that the calamities are caused by [[global warming]], Will realizes his dream as a caveman could be related. Later, Will is chided by the others for not committing himself to his relationship with Amy.\n\nThe gang leaves the garage and Will gets a call from Amy, where he admits his feelings for her before the call is dropped. He decides to go to rescue Amy. Lisa is later killed by a meteor. While the others comfort a distraught Calvin, [[Giselle (Disney)|Giselle]] (Parker), a prostitute, climbs out of a [[manhole]] and gets hit by a [[Taxicab|taxi]]. Calvin catches her, and they [[Love at first sight|immediately fall in love with each other]]. Giselle's [[Procuring (prostitution)|pimp]], [[Enchanted (2007 film)|Prince Edwin]] ([[Tad Hilgenbrink]]), challenges Calvin to [[Step Up 2: The Streets|a dance fight]] for her love, but [[Twister (1996 film)|a tornado]] appears and Prince Edwin escapes. [[Iron Man (2008 film)|Iron Man]] (Gerrard Fachinni), [[Hellboy]] (Barinholtz), and [[The Incredible Hulk (film)|the Hulk]] ([[Roland Kickinger]]) attempt to fight it, but all are defeated by [[Cattle|cows]] thrown by the tornado. After taking shelter, Will, Juney, Calvin, and Giselle encounter [[Rabies|rabid]] knockoffs of [[Alvin and the Chipmunks]], who attack the gang and kill Juney. The \"Chipmunks\" then go after Will and Calvin, but they trap them in a trash can, fatally suffocating them as they attempt to escape.\n\nOn their way to the museum where Amy is trapped, the group runs into [[Batman]], who informs them that they must go to evacuation buses and that there will be no chance of survival if they go to save Amy. With time against them, Princess Giselle kills [[Speed Racer (film)|Speed Racer]] (Jared S. Eddo), and the group hijacks his [[Mach Five]] to drive to the museum. At the museum, they save Amy, who reveals that the Crystal Skull is the only thing that can stop the end of the world. Calvin and the Princess then find that the museum doors are closed and all of the artifacts have [[Night at the Museum|come alive]], including [[Po (Kung Fu Panda)|Po from Kung Fu Panda]] (Yoshio Iizuka), who fights Calvin but is defeated. When Calvin makes out with the Princess, Calvin accidentally pulls her [[wig]] and discovers that she is actually a [[Transvestism|transvestite]]. While this happens, \"Po\" takes out a [[katana]] and simultaneously kills Calvin and the Princess.\n\nMeanwhile, Will and Amy run into a nude [[Beowulf (hero)|Beowulf]] (Barinholtz), who fights with Will. After Amy stabs \"Beowulf\" in the back, Will and Amy encounter [[Indiana Jones]] ([[Tony Cox (actor)|Tony Cox]]), who is revealed to be Will's father. \"Indy\" tries to put the Crystal Skull on the altar, but he flys through a stained glass window in the room. Will does it instead, and he averts further destruction. Will and Amy have a [[wedding]] ceremony performed by [[The Love Guru|\"The Guru Shitka\"]] (Domenico), it then goes to an extensive musical number about all of the characters dating each other (fucking in the unrated version) parodying \"I'm Fucking Matt Damon\" by Sarah Silverman. The film ends with the \"Chipmunks\" getting crushed to death by a falling cow.\n\n== Parodies ==\n{{unrefsec|date=February 2020}}\n=== Films and TV shows ===\n<!-- DO NOT ADD AN ITEM WITHOUT A CITATION TO A RELIABLE SOURCE. IT WILL BE REMOVED IMMEDIATELY. -->\n{{div col}}\n*[[10,000 BC (film)|''10,000 BC'']] (2008)\n*[[American Gladiators (2008 TV series)|''American Gladiators'']] (2008)\n*''[[Indiana Jones and the Kingdom of the Crystal Skull]]'' (2008)\n*''[[The Break-Up]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Flavor of Love]]'' (2006-2008)\n*''[[My Super Sweet 16]]'' (2005-2008)\n*[[Superbad (film)|''Superbad'']] (2007)\n*''[[Women of Wrestling]]'' (2000-2002)\n*[[Wanted (2008 film)|''Wanted'']] (2008)\n*''[[No Country for Old Men (film)|No Country for Old Men]]'' (2007)\n*[[Juno (film)|''Juno'']] (2007)\n*''[[High School Musical]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Cloverfield]]'' (2008)\n*''[[The Day After Tomorrow]]'' (2004)\n*''[[Hannah Montana]]'' (2006-2011)\n*[[Hancock (film)|''Hancock'']] (2008)\n*[[Sex and the City (film)|''Sex and the City'']] (2008)\n*''[[You Don't Mess with the Zohan]]'' (2008)\n*[[Jumper (2008 film)|''Jumper'']] (2008)\n*''[[Drillbit Taylor]]'' (2008)\n*''[[The Chronicles of Narnia: Prince Caspian]]'' (2008)\n*[[Enchanted (film)|''Enchanted'']] (2007)\n*''[[Step Up 2: The Streets]]'' (2008)\n*[[World Trade Center (film)|''World Trade Center'']] (2006)\n*''[[An Inconvenient Truth]]'' (2006)\n*''[[The Matrix Revolutions]]'' (2003)\n*''[[Never Back Down]]'' (2008)\n*[[Twister (1996 film)|''Twister'']] (1996)\n*''[[There Will Be Blood]]'' (2007)\n*[[Doomsday (2008 film)|''Doomsday'']] (2008)\n*[[Iron Man (2008 film)|''Iron Man'']] (2008)\n*[[Hellboy (2004 film)|''Hellboy'']] (2004)\n*[[The Incredible Hulk (film)|''The Incredible Hulk'']] (2008)\n*[[Alvin and the Chipmunks (film)|''Alvin and the Chipmunks'']] (2007)\n*''[[Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me]]'' (1999)\n*[[The Simpsons Movie|''The Simpson\u2019s Movie'']] (2007) - film poster<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/new/Disaster-Movie-Parodies-Simpsons-9106.html|title=Disaster Movie Parodies The Simpsons|date=2008-06-09|website=CINEMABLEND|access-date=2019-09-05}}</ref>\n*[[The Shining (film)|''The Shining'']] (1980)\n*[[HeadOn]] (2006 commercial)\n*[[The Dark Knight (film)|''The Dark Knight'']] (2008)\n*[[Speed Racer (film)|''Speed Racer'']] (2008)\n*[[Armageddon (1998 film)|''Armageddon'']] (1998)\n*''[[Night at the Museum]]'' (2006)\n*[[Beowulf (2007 film)|''Beowulf'']] (2007)\n*''[[Kung Fu Panda]]'' (2008)\n*''[[The Love Guru]]'' (2008)\n{{div col end}}\n<!-- DO NOT ADD AN ITEM WITHOUT A CITATION TO A RELIABLE SOURCE. IT WILL BE REMOVED IMMEDIATELY. -->\n=== Real-life people ===\n{{div col}}\n<!-- DO NOT ADD AN ITEM WITHOUT A CITATION TO A RELIABLE SOURCE. IT WILL BE REMOVED IMMEDIATELY. -->\n*[[Amy Winehouse]]\n*[[Flavor Flav]]\n*[[Phil McGraw]]\n*[[Calvin Klein (company)|Calvin Klein underwear model]]\n*[[Kanye West]]\n*[[Jonas Brothers]]\n*[[Justin Timberlake]]\n*[[Jessica Simpson]]\n*[[Michael Jackson]]\n{{div col end}}\n<!-- DO NOT ADD AN ITEM WITHOUT A CITATION TO A RELIABLE SOURCE. IT WILL BE REMOVED IMMEDIATELY. -->\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Matt Lanter]] as Will\n* [[Vanessa Lachey|Vanessa Minnillo]] as Amy\n* Gary \"G Thang\" Johnson as Calvin\n* [[Crista Flanagan]] as [[Juno (film)|Juney]] / [[Miley Stewart|Hannah Montana]]\n* [[Nicole Parker]] as [[Giselle (Disney)|Giselle]] / [[Amy Winehouse]] / [[Jessica Simpson]]\n* [[Kim Kardashian]] as Lisa Taylor\n* [[Ike Barinholtz]] as [[World Trade Center (film)|The Policeman]] / [[Michael Van Wijk|Wolf]] / [[Anton Chigurh]] / [[Hellboy]] / [[Batman]] / [[Beowulf (hero)|\"Beowulf\"]] / [[Prince Caspian (character)|Prince Caspian]]\n* [[Carmen Electra]] as [[Wanted (2008 film)|The Beautiful Assassin]]\n* [[Tony Cox (actor)|Tony Cox]] as [[Indiana Jones]]\n* [[Tad Hilgenbrink]] as [[Enchanted (2007 film)|Prince Edwin]]\n* [[Nick Steele (actor)|Nick Steele]] as [[Calvin Klein|Underwear Model]]\n* Jason Boegh as [[Carrie Bradshaw]]\n* [[Valerie Wildman]] as [[Samantha Jones (Sex and the City)|Samantha Jones]]\n* John Di Domenico as [[Phil McGraw|Dr. Phil]] / [[The Love Guru|The Guru Shitka]]\n* Abe Spigner as [[Flavor Flav]]\n* Christopher Johnson as [[Michael Jackson]]\n* Jared S. Eddo as [[Speed Racer (film)|Speed Racer]]\n* Yoshio Iizuka as [[Po (Kung Fu Panda)|Kung Fu Panda]]\n* Jonas Neal as [[Justin Timberlake|J.T.]]\n* Jacob Tolano Wood as [[Hulk|Dr. Bruce Banner]]\n* [[Roland Kickinger]] as [[Hulk|The Incredible Hulk]]\n* Walter Harris as [[Hancock (film)|John Hancock]]\n* Gerrard Fachinni as [[Iron Man (2008 film)|Iron Man]]\n* Johnny Rock as Male Princess (Enchanted Princess' dance double)\n* Devin Crittenden as [[Juno (film)|Paulie Bleeker]]\n* Noah Harpster as [[Superbad (film)|Seth]]\n* Austin Michael Scott as [[Superbad (film)|McLover]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nOn April 2, 2008, less than 3 months after the release of Friedberg and Seltzer's previous spoof film ''[[Meet the Spartans]]'', it was announced that the duo were in pre-production on a spoof of ''[[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]'', with the title being ''Goodie Two Shoes''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sciretta|first1=Peter|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/tag/goodie-two-shoes/|title=Spoofing SuperBad?|work=SlashFilm|date=April 2, 2008|accessdate=January 10, 2020}}</ref> Unlike the previous Friedberg and Seltzer-directed films, which were financed by [[Regency Enterprises]] and distributed by [[20th Century Fox]], this film was financed by [[Grosvenor Park Productions|Grosvenor Park]] and distributed by [[Lionsgate]] in the United States.\n\n===Writing===\nJason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer wrote the film as a parody of ''Superbad'', but similar to the duo's previous films, it parodies some of the big blockbusters and popular celebrities from 2007 and 2008. Since many of the films being spoofed were not released at the time that the script was being written, Friedberg and Seltzer used trailer footage to get the basic idea of the films.\n\n===Casting===\nOn April 28, [[Matt Lanter]], [[Vanessa Minnillo]], Gary \u201cG Thang\u201d Johnson and [[Carmen Electra]] signed up to be the main cast members.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Parfitt|first1=Orlando|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2008/04/28/meet-the-spartans-duo-at-it-again|title=Meet the Spartans Duo at it Again|work=IGN|date=April 28, 2008|accessdate=January 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nFilming took place in the state of [[Louisiana]] from April 28 to June 6.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sciretta|first1=Peter|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/tag/goodie-two-shoes/|title=Spoofing SuperBad?|work=SlashFilm|date=April 2, 2008|accessdate=January 10, 2020}}</ref> Oscar-nominated production designer William Elliott (who has done production design on the duo films since ''[[Date Movie]]''), did the production design for the sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grantland.com/features/surely-they-cant-be-serious/|title=Surely They Can\u2019t Be Serious? - The unlikely rise of Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer, Hollywood's majorly hated, hugely successful kings of the modern-day spoof|author=Patches, Matt|date=January 31, 2014|work=[[Grantland.com]]|accessdate=January 10, 2020}}</ref> The [[Chamber of commerce]] building in [[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]] was used for filming the natural history museum scenes in the film.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carr|first1=David|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/20/movies/20shre.html|title=Son of a Gun, Hollywood Has Big Fun on the Bayou|work=The New York Times|date=May 20, 2008|accessdate=January 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Post-production===\nAfter the filming had ended, Friedberg and Seltzer renamed the film as ''Disaster Movie''.\n\n==Release==\n===Critical reception===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], ''Disaster Movie'' has an approval rating of 1% based on 73 reviews with an average rating of 1.76/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"Returning to their seemingly bottomless well of flatulence humor, racial stereotypes, and stale pop culture gags, Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer have produced what is arguably their worst ''Movie'' yet.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/disaster_movie/ |title=Disaster Movie (2008) | publisher = [[Fandango Media]] |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date= 2018-12-15 }}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 15 out of 100 based on reviews from 12 critics, indicating \"overwhelming dislike\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/disastermovie |title=Disaster Movie (2008): Reviews |access-date=2008-09-05 |website=[[Metacritic]] }}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film a grade of \"F\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web |url= https://cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title= CinemaScore |work= [[CinemaScore]] |access-date= November 14, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180206073531/https://cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date= February 6, 2018 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\nIt was featured in [[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'s ''50 Worst Movies Ever'' poll,<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\">{{cite web | url = http://www.empireonline.com/features/50-worst-movies-ever/default.asp?film=14 | title = The 50 Worst Movies Ever | work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] | accessdate = 2013-06-03}}</ref> [[Total Film]]'s ''66 Worst Movies Ever'' list<ref name=TotalFilm>{{cite web|url=http://www.totalfilm.com/features/66-worst-movies-of-all-time|title=66 Worst Movies Of All Time|date=2012-02-15|work=[[Total Film]]|accessdate=2013-09-30}}</ref> and the [[Movie Review Query Engine|MRQE]]'s 50 Worst Movies list (where it holds a score of 17, the lowest score on the site).<ref name=\"MRQE50\">{{cite web |title=50 Worst Movies |work=[[Movie Review Query Engine]] |url=http://www.mrqe.com/movies/special/50_worst_movies |accessdate=2011-03-07}}</ref> ''Disaster Movie'' became the lowest ranked film on [[Internet Movie Database|IMDb]]'s Bottom 100 list days after its premiere.<ref name=\"vh1.com\">{{cite web | url = http://www.vh1.com/celebrity/2008-09-05/update-disaster-movie-is-the-worst-collection-of-things-posing-as-a-movie-of-all-time | title = Disaster Movie is the worst [Collection of things posing as a] movie of all time | work = [[VH1]] | date = 2008-09-05 | accessdate = 2013-04-17 | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130927040609/http://www.vh1.com/celebrity/2008-09-05/update-disaster-movie-is-the-worst-collection-of-things-posing-as-a-movie-of-all-time | archive-date = September 27, 2013 | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Byrnes\">{{cite news|last=Byrnes|first=Paul|title=Disaster Movie|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/entertainment/film/film-reviews/disaster-movie/2008/10/02/1222651235778.html|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=June 3, 2013|date=October 2, 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[Jason Solomons]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' wrote that \"Nothing can convey the grimness of ''Disaster Movie'', which would be the Worst Movie Ever Made were it actually a movie at all.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Solomons|first=Jason|title=Disaster Movie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2008/sep/07/comedy|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=June 3, 2013 | date=September 6, 2008}}</ref> Adam Tobias of the ''[[Watertown Daily Times]]'' opined, \"I just don't see how anyone could not find ''Disaster Movie'' one of the worst films of all time,\" further adding that the title of the film was appropriate, because the movie is \"a disaster.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Tobias|first=Adam|title=Disaster Movie one of the worst films of all time|url=http://www.wdtimes.com/features/screen_scenes/article_a665de71-6454-5ce5-9454-d13b9ad9ee18.html|work=[[Watertown Daily Times]]|accessdate=June 3, 2013|date=September 5, 2008}}</ref>  ''[[The Times]]'' newspaper named the film the worst of 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article5245052.ece?token=null&offset=84&page=8 |title=The 100 Worst Movies of 2008 |access-date=2009-12-12|publisher=The Times | location=London | date=2008-12-08 |first1=Anushka |last1=Asthana|author-link1=Anushka Asthana}}</ref>\n\nThe only positive review posted on Rotten Tomatoes was by Jim Schembri from Australian newspaper ''[[The Age]]''. Schembri called it \"dumb but also undeniably funny in more spots than a right-thinking mature person feels comfortable admitting\", the film was given 3\u00bd stars out of five.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/entertainment/film/film-reviews/disaster-movie/2008/10/09/1223145526498.html|title= Disaster Movie Review | work=The Age | access-date=October 9, 2008|location=Melbourne|first1=Jim|last1=Schembri}}</ref>\n\nThe most positive major critic review listed on either [[Metacritic]] or Rotten Tomatoes was by [[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', who gave the film a C+ and remarked: \"The movie is merciless sending up ''[[Juno (film)|Juno]]''{{'}}s self-satisfied hipster gobbledygook, and it's quite funny to see [[Hannah Montana]] still promoting her tie-in products as she lies crushed and dying under a meteor.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20222674,00.html |title= Movie Review |accessdate=2008-09-03 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] }}</ref> Gleiberman previously contributed the only positive review listed on either site (out of 17 at Metacritic and 57 at Rotten Tomatoes) of Friedberg and Seltzer's earlier effort ''[[Epic Movie]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/epic_movie/ |title=Epic Movie (2007)  |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date= 2018-12-15 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/epic-movie |title=Epic Movie (2007): Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |access-date=2008-08-30 }}</ref>\n\nIn a 2017 episode of the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] show ''[[Big Fan (game show)|Big Fan]]'', Kim Kardashian revealed that she is \u201cmortified\u201d by her character's death scene in the film and she \"can\u2019t watch\u201d [it].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Beresford|first1=Trilby|url=https://hellogiggles.com/reviews-coverage/movies/kim-kardashian-admitted-the-project-shes-now-embarrassed-of/|title=Kim Kardashian admitted the thing she's now most embarrassed of, and we actually don't think it's all that bad|work=Hello Giggles|date=January 17, 2017|accessdate=January 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Box office performance===\n{{Anchor|Box Office}}\nOn its domestic theatrical debut, ''Disaster Movie'' grossed $2,023,130 on its opening day, $5,836,973 over the three-day weekend, and $6,945,535 over the four-day weekend (including [[Labor Day]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=daily&id=disastermovie.htm | title=Daily Box Office Grosses for ''Disaster Movie'' (2008)| publisher=Box Office Mojo | accessdate=2008-09-01}}</ref> It ranked #7 for both the three- and four-day weekends. The film's takings for the weekend fell far short of the $17 million predicted by the ''[[Dallas Morning News]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/ent/stories/DN-boxofficebuzz_0829gl.ART.State.Edition1.4d574d9.html | title=Box Office Buzz | work=Dallas Morning News | date=August 29, 2008 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205234153/http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/ent/stories/DN-boxofficebuzz_0829gl.ART.State.Edition1.4d574d9.html | archivedate=December 5, 2008}}</ref> The film was not as commercially successful as previous Friedberg/Seltzer releases. On a $20 million budget, it grossed $14,190,901 domestically and $17,492,474 overseas for a worldwide total of $31,683,375,<ref name=\"bom\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=disastermovie.htm | title=Disaster Movie (2008) | website=[[Box Office Mojo]] | access-date=2008-11-13}}</ref> less than half the gross of ''[[Meet the Spartans]]''.\n\n==Home media==\nThe [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] was released on January 6, 2009. They both included an Unrated \"Cataclysmic\" Edition and a theatrical version, both with the same extras. About 410,934 DVD units were sold, bringing in $8,447,690 in revenue (updated October 2009).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2008/DISAT-DVD.php |title=Disaster Movie - DVD Sales |publisher=The Numbers |date= |accessdate=2011-05-07}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\nOn January 21, 2009, the film received six nominations for the [[29th Golden Raspberry Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.razzies.com/history/29thNoms.asp|title=Razzies.com 2008 Nominations|author=John Wilson|publisher=Razzie Awards|date=2009-01-21|accessdate=2009-01-21|authorlink=John Wilson (Golden Raspberry)|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430040643/http://www.razzies.com/history/29thnoms.asp|archivedate=April 30, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The nominations were for Worst Picture, Worst Supporting Actress (Electra), Worst Supporting Actress (Kardashian), Worst Director, Worst Screenplay, and Worst Prequel, Remake, Rip-Off, or Sequel. [[Kim Kardashian|Kardashian]] acknowledged her nomination on her blog, where she commented, \"It's an honor just being nominated!\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://kimkardashian.celebuzz.com/2009/01/my-first-razzie-nomination.php | title=Kim in the News: My first Razzie nomination! | work=kimkardashian.celebuzz.com | date=January 21, 2009 | accessdate=September 25, 2016 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090124193241/http://kimkardashian.celebuzz.com/2009/01/my-first-razzie-nomination.php | archivedate=January 24, 2009}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Association\n! Category\n! Recipient(s)\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\"| 2009\n| rowspan=\"6\"| [[29th Golden Raspberry Awards]]\n| [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Picture|Worst Picture]]\n| [[Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer|Jason Friedberg, Aaron Seltzer]], and [[Peter Safran]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress|Worst Supporting Actress]]\n| [[Kim Kardashian]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Worst Supporting Actress\n| [[Carmen Electra]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Prequel, Remake, Rip-off or Sequel|Worst Prequel, Remake, Rip-off or Sequel]]\n| \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Director|Worst Director]]\n| Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Screenplay|Worst Screenplay]]\n| Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.disastermovie.net/}}\n* {{IMDb title|1213644|Disaster Movie}}\n* {{mojo title|disastermovie|Disaster Movie}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|disaster_movie|Disaster Movie}}\n* {{metacritic film|disaster-movie|Disaster Movie}}\n\n{{Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Disaster Movie}}\n[[Category:2008 films]]\n[[Category:2000s comedy films]]\n[[Category:2000s parody films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American comedy films]]\n[[Category:American parody films]]\n[[Category:Apocalyptic films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Films about infidelity]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Entertainment One films]]\n[[Category:Icon Productions films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Peter Safran]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2008 American parody film}}\n{{For|the genre|Disaster film}}\n{{pp-pc1}}{{Use American English|date = October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Disaster Movie\n| image = Disaster movie.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer|Jason Friedberg<br />Aaron Seltzer]]\n| producers = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Peter Safran]]\n* Jason Friedberg\n* Aaron Seltzer\n}}\n| writers = {{Plainlist|\n* Jason Friedberg\n* Aaron Seltzer\n}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Matt Lanter]]\n* [[Vanessa Minnillo]]\n* Gary \"G Thang\" Johnson\n* [[Kim Kardashian]]\n* [[Crista Flanagan]]\n* [[Nicole Parker]]\n* [[Ike Barinholtz]]\n* [[Carmen Electra]]\n* [[Tony Cox (actor)|Tony Cox]]\n}}\n| music = [[Christopher Lennertz]]\n| cinematography = Shawn Maurer\n| editing = Peck Prior\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Grosvenor Park Productions|Grosvenor Park]]\n* [[The Safran Company]]\n* 3 in the Box\n}}\n| distributor = [[Lions Gate Entertainment|Lionsgate]]\n| released = {{Film date|2008|08|29}}\n| runtime = 87 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 86:58--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/disaster-movie-2008-0 | title=''Disaster Movie'' (12A) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=August 28, 2008 | accessdate=June 25, 2013}}</ref>\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = $20 million<ref name=\"bom\"/>\n| gross = $34.8 million<ref name=\"bom\"/>\n}}\n'''''Disaster Movie''''' is a 2008 American [[parody film]] written and directed by [[Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer]]. It stars [[Matt Lanter]], [[Vanessa Minnillo]], Gary \"G Thang\" Johnson, [[Crista Flanagan]], [[Nicole Parker]], [[Ike Barinholtz]], [[Carmen Electra]], [[Tony Cox (actor)|Tony Cox]], and [[Kim Kardashian]] in her feature film debut. Released on August 29, 2008 by [[Lionsgate]], the film is a parody of the [[disaster film]] genre and [[pop culture]]. \n\nThe film was panned by critics and audiences for its forced humor, excessive references and poor directing, with many considering it to be worse than the previous movies created by Seltzer and Friedberg,<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/SHOWBIZ/Movies/09/25/decades.worst.movies.tomatoes/ | title=Site picks worst movies of the decade | work=CNN | date=September 25, 2009 | accessdate=September 25, 2016}}</ref> as well as [[List of films considered the worst|one of the worst films of all time]]. The movie received six nominations for the [[29th Golden Raspberry Awards]]. It grossed nearly $35 million against a budget of $20 million.<ref name=\"bom\"/>\n\n==Plot==\nIn the year [[10,000 BC (film)|10,001 B.C.]], a [[caveman]] runs away from a predator through a plain and immediately gets into a fight with [[Michael Van Wijk|Wolf]] ([[Ike Barinholtz]]). After defeating him, the caveman then encounters the predator, a [[Saber-toothed cat|saber-toothed]], [[gasoline]]-drinking [[Amy Winehouse]] ([[Nicole Parker]]), who informs him that the [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|world will end]] on August 29, 2008 and that their fate lies in a [[Indiana Jones and the Kingdom of the Crystal Skull|Crystal Skull]]. The sequence is then revealed to be a dream of [[everyman]] Will ([[Matt Lanter]]) in the present day. He then finds out that his girlfriend Amy ([[Vanessa Minnillo]]) is having an affair with [[Flavor Flav]] (Abe Spigner), and she breaks up with Will because he is not admitting his true feelings for her.\n\nLater that day, Will has a \"[[My Super Sweet 16|Super Duper Sweet Sixteen]]\" party at his house, despite being 25. The guests include [[Juno (film)|Juney]] ([[Crista Flanagan]]), [[Phil McGraw|Dr. Phil]] (John Di Domenico), Will's best friend Calvin (Gary \"G Thang\" Johnson), and [[Anton Chigurh]] (Barinholtz), among others. During the party, Amy arrives with her new boyfriend, a [[Calvin Klein]] underwear model. The party then comes to a halt when the room shakes and the lights go out. A bulletin on the radio claims there is a [[meteor shower]] and it is the end of the world. Soon after, the city starts to [[The Day After Tomorrow|freeze over]], and Will, Juney, Calvin, and Calvin's girlfriend Lisa ([[Kim Kardashian]]) retreat to a garage for shelter. When Juney mentions that the calamities are caused by [[global warming]], Will realizes his dream as a caveman could be related. Later, Will is chided by the others for not committing himself to his relationship with Amy.\n\nThe gang leaves the garage and Will gets a call from Amy, where he admits his feelings for her before the call is dropped. He decides to go to rescue Amy. Lisa is later killed by a meteor. While the others comfort a distraught Calvin, [[Giselle (Disney)|Giselle]] (Parker), a prostitute, climbs out of a [[manhole]] and gets hit by a [[Taxicab|taxi]]. Calvin catches her, and they [[Love at first sight|immediately fall in love with each other]]. Giselle's [[Procuring (prostitution)|pimp]], [[Enchanted (2007 film)|Prince Edwin]] ([[Tad Hilgenbrink]]), challenges Calvin to [[Step Up 2: The Streets|a dance fight]] for her love, but [[Twister (1996 film)|a tornado]] appears and Prince Edwin escapes. [[Iron Man (2008 film)|Iron Man]] (Gerrard Fachinni), [[Hellboy]] (Barinholtz), and [[The Incredible Hulk (film)|the Hulk]] ([[Roland Kickinger]]) attempt to fight it, but all are defeated by [[Cattle|cows]] thrown by the tornado. After taking shelter, Will, Juney, Calvin, and Giselle encounter [[Rabies|rabid]] knockoffs of [[Alvin and the Chipmunks]], who attack the gang and kill Juney. The \"Chipmunks\" then go after Will and Calvin, but they trap them in a trash can, fatally suffocating them as they attempt to escape.\n\nOn their way to the museum where Amy is trapped, the group runs into [[Batman]], who informs them that they must go to evacuation buses and that there will be no chance of survival if they go to save Amy. With time against them, Princess Giselle kills [[Speed Racer (film)|Speed Racer]] (Jared S. Eddo), and the group hijacks his [[Mach Five]] to drive to the museum. At the museum, they save Amy, who reveals that the Crystal Skull is the only thing that can stop the end of the world. Calvin and the Princess then find that the museum doors are closed and all of the artifacts have [[Night at the Museum|come alive]], including [[Po (Kung Fu Panda)|Po from Kung Fu Panda]] (Yoshio Iizuka), who fights Calvin but is defeated. When Calvin makes out with the Princess, Calvin accidentally pulls her [[wig]] and discovers that she is actually a [[Transvestism|transvestite]]. While this happens, \"Po\" takes out a [[katana]] and simultaneously kills Calvin and the Princess.\n\nMeanwhile, Will and Amy run into a nude [[Beowulf (hero)|Beowulf]] (Barinholtz), who fights with Will. After Amy stabs \"Beowulf\" in the back, Will and Amy encounter [[Indiana Jones]] ([[Tony Cox (actor)|Tony Cox]]), who is revealed to be Will's father. \"Indy\" tries to put the Crystal Skull on the altar, but he flys through a stained glass window in the room. Will does it instead, and he averts further destruction. Will and Amy have a [[wedding]] ceremony performed by [[The Love Guru|\"The Guru Shitka\"]] (Domenico), it then goes to a extensive musical number about all of the characters dating each other (fucking in the unrated version) parodying \"I'm Fucking Matt Damon\" by Sarah Silverman. The film ends with the \"Chipmunks\" getting crushed to death by a falling cow.\n\n== Parodies ==\n{{unrefsec|date=February 2020}}\n=== Films and TV shows ===\n<!-- DO NOT ADD AN ITEM WITHOUT A CITATION TO A RELIABLE SOURCE. IT WILL BE REMOVED IMMEDIATELY. -->\n{{div col}}\n*[[10,000 BC (film)|''10,000 BC'']] (2008)\n*[[American Gladiators (2008 TV series)|''American Gladiators'']] (2008)\n*''[[Indiana Jones and the Kingdom of the Crystal Skull]]'' (2008)\n*''[[The Break-Up]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Flavor of Love]]'' (2006-2008)\n*''[[My Super Sweet 16]]'' (2005-2008)\n*[[Superbad (film)|''Superbad'']] (2007)\n*''[[Women of Wrestling]]'' (2000-2002)\n*[[Wanted (2008 film)|''Wanted'']] (2008)\n*''[[No Country for Old Men (film)|No Country for Old Men]]'' (2007)\n*[[Juno (film)|''Juno'']] (2007)\n*''[[High School Musical]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Cloverfield]]'' (2008)\n*''[[The Day After Tomorrow]]'' (2004)\n*''[[Hannah Montana]]'' (2006-2011)\n*[[Hancock (film)|''Hancock'']] (2008)\n*[[Sex and the City (film)|''Sex and the City'']] (2008)\n*''[[You Don't Mess with the Zohan]]'' (2008)\n*[[Jumper (2008 film)|''Jumper'']] (2008)\n*''[[Drillbit Taylor]]'' (2008)\n*''[[The Chronicles of Narnia: Prince Caspian]]'' (2008)\n*[[Enchanted (film)|''Enchanted'']] (2007)\n*''[[Step Up 2: The Streets]]'' (2008)\n*[[World Trade Center (film)|''World Trade Center'']] (2006)\n*''[[An Inconvenient Truth]]'' (2006)\n*''[[The Matrix Revolutions]]'' (2003)\n*''[[Never Back Down]]'' (2008)\n*[[Twister (1996 film)|''Twister'']] (1996)\n*''[[There Will Be Blood]]'' (2007)\n*[[Doomsday (2008 film)|''Doomsday'']] (2008)\n*[[Iron Man (2008 film)|''Iron Man'']] (2008)\n*[[Hellboy (2004 film)|''Hellboy'']] (2004)\n*[[The Incredible Hulk (film)|''The Incredible Hulk'']] (2008)\n*[[Alvin and the Chipmunks (film)|''Alvin and the Chipmunks'']] (2007)\n*''[[Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me]]'' (1999)\n*[[The Simpsons Movie|''The Simpson\u2019s Movie'']] (2007) - film poster<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/new/Disaster-Movie-Parodies-Simpsons-9106.html|title=Disaster Movie Parodies The Simpsons|date=2008-06-09|website=CINEMABLEND|access-date=2019-09-05}}</ref>\n*[[The Shining (film)|''The Shining'']] (1980)\n*[[HeadOn]] (2006 commercial)\n*[[The Dark Knight (film)|''The Dark Knight'']] (2008)\n*[[Speed Racer (film)|''Speed Racer'']] (2008)\n*[[Armageddon (1998 film)|''Armageddon'']] (1998)\n*''[[Night at the Museum]]'' (2006)\n*[[Beowulf (2007 film)|''Beowulf'']] (2007)\n*''[[Kung Fu Panda]]'' (2008)\n*''[[The Love Guru]]'' (2008)\n{{div col end}}\n<!-- DO NOT ADD AN ITEM WITHOUT A CITATION TO A RELIABLE SOURCE. IT WILL BE REMOVED IMMEDIATELY. -->\n=== Real-life people ===\n{{div col}}\n<!-- DO NOT ADD AN ITEM WITHOUT A CITATION TO A RELIABLE SOURCE. IT WILL BE REMOVED IMMEDIATELY. -->\n*[[Amy Winehouse]]\n*[[Flavor Flav]]\n*[[Phil McGraw]]\n*[[Calvin Klein (company)|Calvin Klein underwear model]]\n*[[Kanye West]]\n*[[Jonas Brothers]]\n*[[Justin Timberlake]]\n*[[Jessica Simpson]]\n*[[Michael Jackson]]\n{{div col end}}\n<!-- DO NOT ADD AN ITEM WITHOUT A CITATION TO A RELIABLE SOURCE. IT WILL BE REMOVED IMMEDIATELY. -->\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Matt Lanter]] as Will\n* [[Vanessa Lachey|Vanessa Minnillo]] as Amy\n* Gary \"G Thang\" Johnson as Calvin\n* [[Crista Flanagan]] as [[Juno (film)|Juney]] / [[Miley Stewart|Hannah Montana]]\n* [[Nicole Parker]] as [[Giselle (Disney)|Giselle]] / [[Amy Winehouse]] / [[Jessica Simpson]]\n* [[Kim Kardashian]] as Lisa Taylor\n* [[Ike Barinholtz]] as [[World Trade Center (film)|The Policeman]] / [[Michael Van Wijk|Wolf]] / [[Anton Chigurh]] / [[Hellboy]] / [[Batman]] / [[Beowulf (hero)|\"Beowulf\"]] / [[Prince Caspian (character)|Prince Caspian]]\n* [[Carmen Electra]] as [[Wanted (2008 film)|The Beautiful Assassin]]\n* [[Tony Cox (actor)|Tony Cox]] as [[Indiana Jones]]\n* [[Tad Hilgenbrink]] as [[Enchanted (2007 film)|Prince Edwin]]\n* [[Nick Steele (actor)|Nick Steele]] as [[Calvin Klein|Underwear Model]]\n* Jason Boegh as [[Carrie Bradshaw]]\n* [[Valerie Wildman]] as [[Samantha Jones (Sex and the City)|Samantha Jones]]\n* John Di Domenico as [[Phil McGraw|Dr. Phil]] / [[The Love Guru|The Guru Shitka]]\n* Abe Spigner as [[Flavor Flav]]\n* Christopher Johnson as [[Michael Jackson]]\n* Jared S. Eddo as [[Speed Racer (film)|Speed Racer]]\n* Yoshio Iizuka as [[Po (Kung Fu Panda)|Kung Fu Panda]]\n* Jonas Neal as [[Justin Timberlake|J.T.]]\n* Jacob Tolano Wood as [[Hulk|Dr. Bruce Banner]]\n* [[Roland Kickinger]] as [[Hulk|The Incredible Hulk]]\n* Walter Harris as [[Hancock (film)|John Hancock]]\n* Gerrard Fachinni as [[Iron Man (2008 film)|Iron Man]]\n* Johnny Rock as Male Princess (Enchanted Princess' dance double)\n* Devin Crittenden as [[Juno (film)|Paulie Bleeker]]\n* Noah Harpster as [[Superbad (film)|Seth]]\n* Austin Michael Scott as [[Superbad (film)|McLover]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nOn April 2, 2008, less than 3 months after the release of Friedberg and Seltzer\u2019s previous spoof film ''[[Meet the Spartans]]'', it was announced that the duo were in pre-production on a spoof of ''[[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]'', with the title being ''Goodie Two Shoes''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sciretta|first1=Peter|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/tag/goodie-two-shoes/|title=Spoofing SuperBad?|work=SlashFilm|date=April 2, 2008|accessdate=January 10, 2020}}</ref> Unlike the previous Friedberg and Seltzer-directed films, which were financed by [[Regency Enterprises]] and distributed by [[20th Century Fox]], this film was financed by [[Grosvenor Park Productions|Grosvenor Park]] and distributed by [[Lionsgate]] in the United States.\n\n===Writing===\nJason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer wrote the film as a parody of ''Superbad'', but similar to the duo\u2019s previous films, it parodies some of the big blockbusters and popular celebrities from 2007 and 2008. Since many of the films being spoofed were not released at the time that the script was being written, Friedberg and Seltzer used trailer footage to get the basic idea of the films.\n\n===Casting===\nOn April 28, [[Matt Lanter]], [[Vanessa Minnillo]], Gary \u201cG Thang\u201d Johnson and [[Carmen Electra]] signed up to be the main cast members.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Parfitt|first1=Orlando|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2008/04/28/meet-the-spartans-duo-at-it-again|title=Meet the Spartans Duo at it Again|work=IGN|date=April 28, 2008|accessdate=January 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nFilming took place in the state of [[Louisiana]] from April 28 to June 6.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sciretta|first1=Peter|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/tag/goodie-two-shoes/|title=Spoofing SuperBad?|work=SlashFilm|date=April 2, 2008|accessdate=January 10, 2020}}</ref> Oscar-nominated production designer William Elliott (who has done production design on the duo films since ''[[Date Movie]]''), did the production design for the sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grantland.com/features/surely-they-cant-be-serious/|title=Surely They Can\u2019t Be Serious? - The unlikely rise of Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer, Hollywood's majorly hated, hugely successful kings of the modern-day spoof|author=Patches, Matt|date=January 31, 2014|work=[[Grantland.com]]|accessdate=January 10, 2020}}</ref> The [[Chamber of commerce]] building in [[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]] was used for filming the natural history museum scenes in the film.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carr|first1=David|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/20/movies/20shre.html|title=Son of a Gun, Hollywood Has Big Fun on the Bayou|work=The New York Times|date=May 20, 2008|accessdate=January 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Post-production===\nAfter the filming had ended, Friedberg and Seltzer renamed the film as ''Disaster Movie''.\n\n==Release==\n===Critical reception===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], ''Disaster Movie'' has an approval rating of 1% based on 73 reviews with an average rating of 1.76/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"Returning to their seemingly bottomless well of flatulence humor, racial stereotypes, and stale pop culture gags, Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer have produced what is arguably their worst ''Movie'' yet.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/disaster_movie/ |title=Disaster Movie (2008) | publisher = [[Fandango Media]] |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date= 2018-12-15 }}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 15 out of 100 based on reviews from 12 critics, indicating \"overwhelming dislike\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/disastermovie |title=Disaster Movie (2008): Reviews |access-date=2008-09-05 |website=[[Metacritic]] }}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film a grade of \"F\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web |url= https://cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title= CinemaScore |work= [[CinemaScore]] |access-date= November 14, 2018 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180206073531/https://cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date= February 6, 2018 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\nIt was featured in [[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'s ''50 Worst Movies Ever'' poll,<ref name=\"The 50 Worst Movies Ever\">{{cite web | url = http://www.empireonline.com/features/50-worst-movies-ever/default.asp?film=14 | title = The 50 Worst Movies Ever | work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] | accessdate = 2013-06-03}}</ref> [[Total Film]]'s ''66 Worst Movies Ever'' list<ref name=TotalFilm>{{cite web|url=http://www.totalfilm.com/features/66-worst-movies-of-all-time|title=66 Worst Movies Of All Time|date=2012-02-15|work=[[Total Film]]|accessdate=2013-09-30}}</ref> and the [[Movie Review Query Engine|MRQE]]'s 50 Worst Movies list (where it holds a score of 17, the lowest score on the site).<ref name=\"MRQE50\">{{cite web |title=50 Worst Movies |work=[[Movie Review Query Engine]] |url=http://www.mrqe.com/movies/special/50_worst_movies |accessdate=2011-03-07}}</ref> ''Disaster Movie'' became the lowest ranked film on [[Internet Movie Database|IMDb]]'s Bottom 100 list days after its premiere.<ref name=\"vh1.com\">{{cite web | url = http://www.vh1.com/celebrity/2008-09-05/update-disaster-movie-is-the-worst-collection-of-things-posing-as-a-movie-of-all-time | title = Disaster Movie is the worst [Collection of things posing as a] movie of all time | work = [[VH1]] | date = 2008-09-05 | accessdate = 2013-04-17 | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130927040609/http://www.vh1.com/celebrity/2008-09-05/update-disaster-movie-is-the-worst-collection-of-things-posing-as-a-movie-of-all-time | archive-date = September 27, 2013 | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Byrnes\">{{cite news|last=Byrnes|first=Paul|title=Disaster Movie|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/entertainment/film/film-reviews/disaster-movie/2008/10/02/1222651235778.html|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=June 3, 2013|date=October 2, 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[Jason Solomons]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' wrote that \"Nothing can convey the grimness of ''Disaster Movie'', which would be the Worst Movie Ever Made were it actually a movie at all.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Solomons|first=Jason|title=Disaster Movie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2008/sep/07/comedy|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=June 3, 2013 | date=September 6, 2008}}</ref> Adam Tobias of the ''[[Watertown Daily Times]]'' opined, \"I just don't see how anyone could not find ''Disaster Movie'' one of the worst films of all time,\" further adding that the title of the film was appropriate, because the movie is \"a disaster.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Tobias|first=Adam|title=Disaster Movie one of the worst films of all time|url=http://www.wdtimes.com/features/screen_scenes/article_a665de71-6454-5ce5-9454-d13b9ad9ee18.html|work=[[Watertown Daily Times]]|accessdate=June 3, 2013|date=September 5, 2008}}</ref>  ''[[The Times]]'' newspaper named the film the worst of 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article5245052.ece?token=null&offset=84&page=8 |title=The 100 Worst Movies of 2008 |access-date=2009-12-12|publisher=The Times | location=London | date=2008-12-08 |first1=Anushka |last1=Asthana|author-link1=Anushka Asthana}}</ref>\n\nThe only positive review posted on Rotten Tomatoes was by Jim Schembri from Australian newspaper ''[[The Age]]''. Schembri called it \"dumb but also undeniably funny in more spots than a right-thinking mature person feels comfortable admitting\", the film was given 3\u00bd stars out of five.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/entertainment/film/film-reviews/disaster-movie/2008/10/09/1223145526498.html|title= Disaster Movie Review | work=The Age | access-date=October 9, 2008|location=Melbourne|first1=Jim|last1=Schembri}}</ref>\n\nThe most positive major critic review listed on either [[Metacritic]] or Rotten Tomatoes was by [[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', who gave the film a C+ and remarked: \"The movie is merciless sending up ''[[Juno (film)|Juno]]''{{'}}s self-satisfied hipster gobbledygook, and it's quite funny to see [[Hannah Montana]] still promoting her tie-in products as she lies crushed and dying under a meteor.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20222674,00.html |title= Movie Review |accessdate=2008-09-03 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] }}</ref> Gleiberman previously contributed the only positive review listed on either site (out of 17 at Metacritic and 57 at Rotten Tomatoes) of Friedberg and Seltzer's earlier effort ''[[Epic Movie]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/epic_movie/ |title=Epic Movie (2007)  |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date= 2018-12-15 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/epic-movie |title=Epic Movie (2007): Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |access-date=2008-08-30 }}</ref>\n\nIn a 2017 episode of the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] show ''[[Big Fan (game show)|Big Fan]]'', Kim Kardashian revealed that she is \u201cmortified\u201d by her character\u2019s death scene in the film and she \"can\u2019t watch\u201d [it].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Beresford|first1=Trilby|url=https://hellogiggles.com/reviews-coverage/movies/kim-kardashian-admitted-the-project-shes-now-embarrassed-of/|title=Kim Kardashian admitted the thing she's now most embarrassed of, and we actually don't think it's all that bad|work=Hello Giggles|date=January 17, 2017|accessdate=January 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Box office performance===\n{{Anchor|Box Office}}\nOn its domestic theatrical debut, ''Disaster Movie'' grossed $2,023,130 on its opening day, $5,836,973 over the three-day weekend, and $6,945,535 over the four-day weekend (including [[Labor Day]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=daily&id=disastermovie.htm | title=Daily Box Office Grosses for ''Disaster Movie'' (2008)| publisher=Box Office Mojo | accessdate=2008-09-01}}</ref> It ranked #7 for both the three- and four-day weekends. The film's takings for the weekend fell far short of the $17 million predicted by the ''[[Dallas Morning News]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/ent/stories/DN-boxofficebuzz_0829gl.ART.State.Edition1.4d574d9.html | title=Box Office Buzz | work=Dallas Morning News | date=August 29, 2008 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205234153/http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/ent/stories/DN-boxofficebuzz_0829gl.ART.State.Edition1.4d574d9.html | archivedate=December 5, 2008}}</ref> The film was not as commercially successful as previous Friedberg/Seltzer releases. On a $20 million budget, it grossed $14,190,901 domestically and $17,492,474 overseas for a worldwide total of $31,683,375,<ref name=\"bom\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=disastermovie.htm | title=Disaster Movie (2008) | website=[[Box Office Mojo]] | access-date=2008-11-13}}</ref> less than half the gross of ''[[Meet the Spartans]]''.\n\n==Home media==\nThe [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] was released on January 6, 2009. They both included an Unrated \"Cataclysmic\" Edition and a theatrical version, both with the same extras. About 410,934 DVD units were sold, bringing in $8,447,690 in revenue (updated October 2009).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2008/DISAT-DVD.php |title=Disaster Movie - DVD Sales |publisher=The Numbers |date= |accessdate=2011-05-07}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\nOn January 21, 2009, the film received six nominations for the [[29th Golden Raspberry Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.razzies.com/history/29thNoms.asp|title=Razzies.com 2008 Nominations|author=John Wilson|publisher=Razzie Awards|date=2009-01-21|accessdate=2009-01-21|authorlink=John Wilson (Golden Raspberry)|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430040643/http://www.razzies.com/history/29thnoms.asp|archivedate=April 30, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The nominations were for Worst Picture, Worst Supporting Actress (Electra), Worst Supporting Actress (Kardashian), Worst Director, Worst Screenplay, and Worst Prequel, Remake, Rip-Off, or Sequel. [[Kim Kardashian|Kardashian]] acknowledged her nomination on her blog, where she commented, \"It's an honor just being nominated!\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://kimkardashian.celebuzz.com/2009/01/my-first-razzie-nomination.php | title=Kim in the News: My first Razzie nomination! | work=kimkardashian.celebuzz.com | date=January 21, 2009 | accessdate=September 25, 2016 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090124193241/http://kimkardashian.celebuzz.com/2009/01/my-first-razzie-nomination.php | archivedate=January 24, 2009}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Association\n! Category\n! Recipient(s)\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\"| 2009\n| rowspan=\"6\"| [[29th Golden Raspberry Awards]]\n| [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Picture|Worst Picture]]\n| [[Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer|Jason Friedberg, Aaron Seltzer]], and [[Peter Safran]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Supporting Actress|Worst Supporting Actress]]\n| [[Kim Kardashian]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Worst Supporting Actress\n| [[Carmen Electra]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Prequel, Remake, Rip-off or Sequel|Worst Prequel, Remake, Rip-off or Sequel]]\n| \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Director|Worst Director]]\n| Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Screenplay|Worst Screenplay]]\n| Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.disastermovie.net/}}\n* {{IMDb title|1213644|Disaster Movie}}\n* {{mojo title|disastermovie|Disaster Movie}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|disaster_movie|Disaster Movie}}\n* {{metacritic film|disaster-movie|Disaster Movie}}\n\n{{Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Disaster Movie}}\n[[Category:2008 films]]\n[[Category:2000s comedy films]]\n[[Category:2000s parody films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American comedy films]]\n[[Category:American parody films]]\n[[Category:Apocalyptic films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jason Friedberg and Aaron Seltzer]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Films about infidelity]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Entertainment One films]]\n[[Category:Icon Productions films]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Peter Safran]]\n"