he permanent collection at [[The Cleveland Museum of Art]] is an oil painting entitled ''Alpine Landscape: The Handegg, Switzerland'' by French painter and sculptor [[Jean-L\u00e9on G\u00e9r\u00f4me]] which depicts the beauty of this locale still today, as it was during his world travels in the 1850s.<ref>[http://www.clevelandart.org/art/1980.262]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in the canton of Bern]]\n\n\n{{berne-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{See Wiktionary|the village in Switzerland}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n | name                           = Handegg\n | official_name                  = Handegg\n | native_name                    =\n | settlement_type                = Village\n |image_skyline                   = Handegg Grimselpassstrasse pano.jpg\n |imagesize                       = 300px\n |image_caption                   = Grimsel Pass road to Handegg\n | image_map                      =\n | map_caption                    =\n | subdivision_type               = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n | subdivision_name               = Switzerland\n | subdivision_type1              = Canton\n | subdivision_name1              = [[Canton of Bern|Bern]]\n | subdivision_type2              = District\n | subdivision_name2              = [[Interlaken-Oberhasli]]\n | subdivision_type3              = Municipality\n | subdivision_name3              = [[Guttannen]]\n | area_total_km2                 =\n | area_footnotes                 = <ref>[http://epp.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/tgm/table.do?tab=table&init=1&language=en&pcode=tgs00002&plugin=1 Total area and land area, by NUTS 2 regions \u2013 km2]</ref>\n | population_as_of            =\n | population_total            =\n | population_footnotes           =\n | population_density_km2         =\n | elevation_m                    = 1423\n | coordinates                    = {{coord|46|37|N|8|18|E|display=inline}}\n }}\n\n'''Handegg''' (''Handeck'') is a village in the municipality of [[Guttannen]], [[Switzerland]],<ref>[http://veloland.myswitzerland.com/en/services/places/ort-0287.html]</ref> near the lake [[Gelmersee]]. The lake may be reached by [[Gelmerbahn]] from Handegg.\n\n==Geography==\nHandegg is located approximately 46&nbsp;miles (75&nbsp;km) east of [[Bern]] and 39&nbsp;miles (63&nbsp;km) northwest of [[Locarno]].\n\n==Culture==\nPart of the permanent collection at [[The Cleveland Museum of Art]] is an oil painting entitled ''Alpine Landscape: The Handegg, Switzerland'' by French painter and sculptor [[Jean-L\u00e9on G\u00e9r\u00f4me]] which depicts the beauty of this locale still today, as it was during his world travels in the 1850s.<ref>[http://www.clevelandart.org/art/1980.262]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in the canton of Bern]]\n\n\n{{berne-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Handegg"}
{"title_page": "Hal\u00e1sztelek", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- General information -->\n|official_name          =Hal\u00e1sztelek\n|image_shield           =Coa_Hungary_Town_Hal\u00e1sztelek.svg\n|image_flag             =Flag of Hal\u00e1sztelek.svg\n|image_skyline          =Malonyai-kast\u00e9ly (7073. sz\u00e1m\u00fa m\u0171eml\u00e9k) 2.jpg\n|image_caption          =Malonyai Palace\n<!-- Pushpin map -->\n|pushpin_map            =Hungary\n|pushpin_map_caption    =Location of Hal\u00e1sztelek in Hungary\n<!-- Political information -->\n|subdivision_type       =Country\n|subdivision_name       =[[Hungary]]\n|subdivision_type1      =[[List of regions of Hungary|Region]]\n|subdivision_name1      =[[{{Hungarian county region|Pest}}]]\n|subdivision_type2      =[[Counties of Hungary|County]]\n|subdivision_name2      ={{Hungarian county link|Pest}}\n|subdivision_type3      =[[Subregions of Hungary|Subregion]]\n|subdivision_name3      =[[R\u00e1ckeve]]\n|subdivision_type6      =Rank\n|subdivision_name6      ={{Hungarian settlement rank|v\u00e1ros}}\n|leader_title           =Mayor\n|leader_name            =J\u00f3zsef Szentgy\u00f6rgyi<br/><small>[[Hungarian Socialist Party]], \"MSZP\"</small>\n<!-- Geographical information -->\n|area_total_km2         =8.64\n|area_magnitude         =1 E6\n|area_footnotes         =<ref name=\"ksh_cite_area\">[http://www.ksh.hu/apps/!cp.hnt2.telep?nn=09690 Hal\u00e1sztelek] at the [[Hungarian Central Statistical Office]] (Hungarian).</ref>\n|coordinates            ={{coord|47|21|39|N|18|59|16|E|region:HU|display=inline}}\n<!-- Demographical information -->\n|postal_code            =2314\n|postal_code_type       =[[Postal code]]\n|area_code              =+36 24\n|area_code_type         =[[Telephone numbers in Hungary|Area code]]\n|timezone               =[[Central European Time|CET]]\n|utc_offset             =+1\n|timezone_DST           =[[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST         =+2\n|total_type             =Total\n|population_total       =8620\n|population_density_km2 =auto\n|population_density_urban_km2 =auto\n|population_density_metro_km2 =auto\n|population_as_of       =2009\n|population_footnotes   =<ref name=\"ksh_cite_population\">[http://www.ksh.hu/apps/!cp.hnt2.telep?nn=09690 Hal\u00e1sztelek] at the [[Hungarian Central Statistical Office]] (Hungarian). 2009</ref>\n\n|blank_name             =[[Hungarian Central Statistical Office|KSH code]]\n|blank_info             =09690<ref name=\"ksh_cite_area\">[http://www.ksh.hu/apps/!cp.hnt2.telep?nn=09690 Hal\u00e1sztelek] at the [[Hungarian Central Statistical Office]] (Hungarian).</ref>\n|website                =[http://www.halasztelek.hu www.halasztelek.hu]\n}}\n'''Hal\u00e1sztelek''' is a {{lc:{{Hungarian settlement rank|v\u00e1ros}}}} in {{Hungarian county name|Pest}}, [[Hungary]]. Hal\u00e1sztelek lies on the north part of [[Csepel Island]], on the [[Danube]].\n\n== History ==\nThe Romans, during their occupation, found Hal\u00e1sztelek dangerous because of the regular flooding of the Danube. It is likely that [[Attila the Hun]] started his attacks here against the Roman fortress which may have been at [[Sz\u00e1zhalombatta]]. The occupying Hungarians from East Asia used Csepel Island as a summer retreat, and [[Sz\u0151l\u0151s]], [[H\u00e1ros]] and [[T\u00f6k\u00f6l]] grew into settlements over time.\n\nAt the end of the 19th century the population of Hal\u00e1sztelek numbered no more than fifty.\n\nThe settlement was named after [[Ern\u0151 Warmann]]'s sister and was called Herminamajor (\"Hermina's field\") or Herminatelep (\"Hermina's land\"). The next owner was P\u00e1l S\u00e1ndor who grew melons. As agriculture became more developed, the population started to increase and in 1920 it reached 254 people. Not much later, the settlement had new owners in the Malonyay family, whose castle was famed for its balls. During the world economic crisis of the 1930s the family went bankrupt and workers and Bulgarian families started to buy parts of their estate (which is why signs at the city limits are in both [[Cyrillic script|Cyrillic]] and [[Latin alphabet]]s). After these sales of the estate, the castle's value was greatly reduced, and [[Istv\u00e1n F\u00fczessy]] became its owner. It is said that he lost the castle in a card game to [[Emil Stein]]. Stein planted peach orchards, and the land around the castle is still known as such, even though the land is now used for housing.\n\nAfter [[World War II]] the population rapidly increased, especially with migration from [[{{Hungarian county name|Zala}}]], [[{{Hungarian county name|Szabolcs-Szatm\u00e1r-Bereg}}]], [[{{Hungarian county name|J\u00e1sz-Nagykun-Szolnok}}]] and [[{{Hungarian county name|Hajd\u00fa-Bihar}}]]. In 1949, the population was 1,401.\n\nFrom 1 May 1950 the settlement became an independent village ({{lang-hu|k\u00f6zs\u00e9g}}) called Herminatelep.  In 1951 it changed to its current name of Hal\u00e1sztelek. Around that time the population was around 1,500, but its proximity to Budapest had the population double by 1955.\n\nFrom the 1970s, with the population increase, the settlement became more modernized and 70% of all properties had mains water and electricity. During this time the telephone network was also introduced to the area.\n\nOn 1 July 2008 Hal\u00e1sztelek got status as a city.\n\n==Transport==\nThe [[M0 motorway (Hungary)|M0]] leads to Hal\u00e1sztelek from [[Lakihegy]].\n\nThe transport infrastructure started to develop from the 1950s, and the [[Budapesti K\u00f6zleked\u00e9si Zrt.|BKV]] {{lang|hu|Budapesti K\u00f6zleked\u00e9si V\u00e1llalat}}, \"Mass Transport Company of Budapest\" started to run one bus route, increasing to three in the 1960s. After Communist rule ended, the BKV ended operations, which were taken over by the [[Vol\u00e1nbusz]] company. The increased population led to increasing demands on the roads, and new ones were built.\n\n==Education==\nIn 1944 the T\u00f6k\u00f6l council decided the street names and opened a state school, and in this year education started as a single classroom in M\u00e1ria Szabados\u00e1s apartment, which is now called {{lang|hu|Kisiskola}} (\"Small School\"). A few years later there were two classes, and when the settlement became independent a new school was built. In the 1970s there was a large change in education practice, and in 1971 a vocational school for horticulture opened, called nowadays [[Istv\u00e1n Bocskai]] Reformed Secondary School.\n\n== Notable people ==\n*[[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Cseh]], Hungarian swimmer\n* [[Ferenc N\u00e9meth]] football player\n*[[Bal\u00e1zs H\u00e1rai]], Hungarian Waterball player\n\n==International relations==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Hungary}}\n\n===Twin towns \u2014 Sister cities===\nHal\u00e1sztelek is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n*{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Nikopol, Bulgaria|Nikopol]], [[Bulgaria]]\n\n== Sport ==\n* [[Hal\u00e1sztelek FC]], the city soccer club\n\n== Landmarks ==\n[[File:Hal\u00e1sztelek - Palace.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Aerial photograph of Malonyai castle]]\n\n* [[Malonyay Castle]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Hal\u00e1sztelek}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.halasztelek.hu/}} in Hungarian\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070131182919/http://www.vendegvaro.hu/5-953 Tourist information for Hal\u00e1sztelek] {{in lang|hu}}\n* [http://www.civertan.hu/legifoto/legifoto.php?page_level=224 Aerial photographs of Hal\u00e1sztelek]\n* [http://terkepkalauz.hu/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=647&Itemid=99999999 Map of Hal\u00e1sztelek] \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100101042628/http://www.kastelyok-utazas.hu/Webalbum/Magyar/Kastely/Malonyay/Kepek.html Pictures of Malonyay Castle]\n* [http://sites.google.com/site/reformatuslap/ T\u00f6k\u00f6l-Hal\u00e1sztelek Reformed Church community website] {{in lang|hu}}\n\n{{Szigetszentmikl\u00f3s District}}\n{{Pest County}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Halasztelek}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Pest County]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- General information -->\n|official_name          =Hal\u00e1sztelek\n|image_shield           =Coa_Hungary_Town_Hal\u00e1sztelek.svg\n|image_flag             =Flag of Hal\u00e1sztelek.svg\n|image_skyline          =Malonyai-kast\u00e9ly (7073. sz\u00e1m\u00fa m\u0171eml\u00e9k) 2.jpg\n|image_caption          =Malonyai Palace\n<!-- Pushpin map -->\n|pushpin_map            =Hungary\n|pushpin_map_caption    =Location of Hal\u00e1sztelek in Hungary\n<!-- Political information -->\n|subdivision_type       =Country\n|subdivision_name       =[[Hungary]]\n|subdivision_type1      =[[List of regions of Hungary|Region]]\n|subdivision_name1      =[[{{Hungarian county region|Pest}}]]\n|subdivision_type2      =[[Counties of Hungary|County]]\n|subdivision_name2      ={{Hungarian county link|Pest}}\n|subdivision_type3      =[[Subregions of Hungary|Subregion]]\n|subdivision_name3      =[[R\u00e1ckeve]]\n|subdivision_type6      =Rank\n|subdivision_name6      ={{Hungarian settlement rank|v\u00e1ros}}\n|leader_title           =Mayor\n|leader_name            =J\u00f3zsef Szentgy\u00f6rgyi<br/><small>[[Hungarian Socialist Party]], \"MSZP\"</small>\n<!-- Geographical information -->\n|area_total_km2         =8.64\n|area_magnitude         =1 E6\n|area_footnotes         =<ref name=\"ksh_cite_area\">[http://www.ksh.hu/apps/!cp.hnt2.telep?nn=09690 Hal\u00e1sztelek] at the [[Hungarian Central Statistical Office]] (Hungarian). </ref>\n|coordinates            ={{coord|47|21|39|N|18|59|16|E|region:HU|display=inline}}\n<!-- Demographical information -->\n|postal_code            =2314\n|postal_code_type       =[[Postal code]]\n|area_code              =+36 24\n|area_code_type         =[[Telephone numbers in Hungary|Area code]]\n|timezone               =[[Central European Time|CET]]\n|utc_offset             =+1\n|timezone_DST           =[[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST         =+2\n|total_type             =Total\n|population_total       =8620\n|population_density_km2 =auto\n|population_density_urban_km2 =auto\n|population_density_metro_km2 =auto\n|population_as_of       =2009\n|population_footnotes   =<ref name=\"ksh_cite_population\">[http://www.ksh.hu/apps/!cp.hnt2.telep?nn=09690 Hal\u00e1sztelek] at the [[Hungarian Central Statistical Office]] (Hungarian). 2009</ref>\n\n|blank_name             =[[Hungarian Central Statistical Office|KSH code]]\n|blank_info             =09690<ref name=\"KSHcite\">[http://www.ksh.hu/apps/!cp.hnt2.telep?nn=09690 Hal\u00e1sztelek] at the [[Hungarian Central Statistical Office]] (Hungarian).</ref>\n|website                =[http://www.halasztelek.hu www.halasztelek.hu]\n}}\n'''Hal\u00e1sztelek''' is a {{lc:{{Hungarian settlement rank|v\u00e1ros}}}} in {{Hungarian county name|Pest}}, [[Hungary]]. Hal\u00e1sztelek lies on the north part of [[Csepel Island]], on the [[Danube]].\n\n== History ==\nThe Romans, during their occupation, found Hal\u00e1sztelek dangerous because of the regular flooding of the Danube. It is likely that [[Attila the Hun]] started his attacks here against the Roman fortress which may have been at [[Sz\u00e1zhalombatta]]. The occupying Hungarians from East Asia used Csepel Island as a summer retreat, and [[Sz\u0151l\u0151s]], [[H\u00e1ros]] and [[T\u00f6k\u00f6l]] grew into settlements over time.\n\nAt the end of the 19th century the population of Hal\u00e1sztelek numbered no more than fifty.\n\nThe settlement was named after [[Ern\u0151 Warmann]]'s sister and was called Herminamajor (\"Hermina's field\") or Herminatelep (\"Hermina's land\"). The next owner was P\u00e1l S\u00e1ndor who grew melons. As agriculture became more developed, the population started to increase and in 1920 it reached 254 people. Not much later, the settlement had new owners in the Malonyay family, whose castle was famed for its balls. During the world economic crisis of the 1930s the family went bankrupt and workers and Bulgarian families started to buy parts of their estate (which is why signs at the city limits are in both [[Cyrillic script|Cyrillic]] and [[Latin alphabet]]s). After these sales of the estate, the castle's value was greatly reduced, and [[Istv\u00e1n F\u00fczessy]] became its owner. It is said that he lost the castle in a card game to [[Emil Stein]]. Stein planted peach orchards, and the land around the castle is still known as such, even though the land is now used for housing.\n\nAfter [[World War II]] the population rapidly increased, especially with migration from [[{{Hungarian county name|Zala}}]], [[{{Hungarian county name|Szabolcs-Szatm\u00e1r-Bereg}}]], [[{{Hungarian county name|J\u00e1sz-Nagykun-Szolnok}}]] and [[{{Hungarian county name|Hajd\u00fa-Bihar}}]]. In 1949, the population was 1,401.\n\nFrom 1 May 1950 the settlement became an independent village ({{lang-hu|k\u00f6zs\u00e9g}}) called Herminatelep.  In 1951 it changed to its current name of Hal\u00e1sztelek. Around that time the population was around 1,500, but its proximity to Budapest had the population double by 1955.\n\nFrom the 1970s, with the population increase, the settlement became more modernized and 70% of all properties had mains water and electricity. During this time the telephone network was also introduced to the area.\n\nOn 1 July 2008 Hal\u00e1sztelek got status as a city.\n\n==Transport==\nThe [[M0 motorway (Hungary)|M0]] leads to Hal\u00e1sztelek from [[Lakihegy]].\n\nThe transport infrastructure started to develop from the 1950s, and the [[Budapesti K\u00f6zleked\u00e9si Zrt.|BKV]] {{lang|hu|Budapesti K\u00f6zleked\u00e9si V\u00e1llalat}}, \"Mass Transport Company of Budapest\" started to run one bus route, increasing to three in the 1960s. After Communist rule ended, the BKV ended operations, which were taken over by the [[Vol\u00e1nbusz]] company. The increased population led to increasing demands on the roads, and new ones were built.\n\n==Education==\nIn 1944 the T\u00f6k\u00f6l council decided the street names and opened a state school, and in this year education started as a single classroom in M\u00e1ria Szabados\u00e1s apartment, which is now called {{lang|hu|Kisiskola}} (\"Small School\"). A few years later there were two classes, and when the settlement became independent a new school was built. In the 1970s there was a large change in education practice, and in 1971 a vocational school for horticulture opened, called nowadays [[Istv\u00e1n Bocskai]] Reformed Secondary School.\n\n== Notable people ==\n*[[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Cseh]], Hungarian swimmer\n* [[Ferenc N\u00e9meth]] football player\n*[[Bal\u00e1zs H\u00e1rai]], Hungarian Waterball player\n\n==International relations==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Hungary}}\n\n===Twin towns \u2014 Sister cities===\nHal\u00e1sztelek is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n*{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Nikopol, Bulgaria|Nikopol]], [[Bulgaria]]\n\n== Sport ==\n* [[Hal\u00e1sztelek FC]], the city soccer club\n\n== Landmarks ==\n[[File:Hal\u00e1sztelek - Palace.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Aerial photograph of Malonyai castle]]\n\n* [[Malonyay Castle]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Hal\u00e1sztelek}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.halasztelek.hu/}} in Hungarian\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070131182919/http://www.vendegvaro.hu/5-953 Tourist information for Hal\u00e1sztelek] {{in lang|hu}}\n* [http://www.civertan.hu/legifoto/legifoto.php?page_level=224 Aerial photographs of Hal\u00e1sztelek]\n* [http://terkepkalauz.hu/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=647&Itemid=99999999 Map of Hal\u00e1sztelek] \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100101042628/http://www.kastelyok-utazas.hu/Webalbum/Magyar/Kastely/Malonyay/Kepek.html Pictures of Malonyay Castle]\n* [http://sites.google.com/site/reformatuslap/ T\u00f6k\u00f6l-Hal\u00e1sztelek Reformed Church community we